commentBody:
For me this was the hardest Monday ever 😮. I needed several lookups in the NW corner - the accumulation of name, brand, unfamiliar instrument and theater terminology was too much for this Polish theaterphobe. Also, SNOb took much longer to spot than I would like to admit, and I was so distracted by how badly my solve was going I almost did not spot GOLDENpOODLE crossing pMS was wrong. I almost had to check the puzzle - on Monday! My struggles probably were down to my being Polish rather than anything being wrong with the puzzle itself but I can't say I enjoyed the experience.

* * *

Reposting below my late reply to replies to my yesterday's comment.

@RozzieGrandma 

When we do a puzzle it takes over our whole dining table - for the 3000 piece puzzles we actually have a huge square of laminated particle board we put on the table to make it even larger so there is room for everything, including the multiple sorting trays. We eat on the sofa anyway so it's not a huge problem 😉. We don't have children and we rarely entertain people at home, which also helps. 

[She is a high ranking manager in our public administration.]

@Jon

Yes, that was what I realized after staring at the clue. When we visited the US years ago we were surprised by how different your traffic signs were to European ones - so much was written down and so little handled with pictograms!

@B

Thanks, I didn't know the thing was called a tamper!

@MRR 
Not just you. The only definitions I know for “snot” are a) as you described, and b) the product of a leaky nose. But I guess T’s are easier to cross than B’s?

@Jane
I was letting “melbs” slide, too, as an abbreviation for some weird sandwich I’d never heard of. MELTS makes much more sense… but SNOT? SRSLY?

@MRR 
Snot is up there with the most vulgar words in the language.  I can't think of a single usage that doesn't have a negative impact.  Snot green? Snot rag? "You little snot!"? Snotty comments? It'snot a word I ever use.

See what I mean?

@Patricia Henry 

I'm guessing that SNOB and SNOT have been conflated in vernacular conversation because a SNOB will look down their nose at others.

Nasal congestion in language.

@Vaer 

Even right here in Gotham, I too had HAM before MAC! Took quite a while to turn my brain around on that one. 

I was going for HEROES as the "often tuna" sandwiches, too. (HOAGIES didn't fit.) I guess I just wasn't feeling all that melty cheese today...

@Nora 
I think constructors often try to be clever or original in the clues they write, but the editors will change any clue they feel is too tricky or obscure for the day. 

I imagine having a clue you came up with accepted by the editors must be almost as satisfying as having your puzzle accepted for publication.  :)

@Jane Wheelaghan 

Yes, GM = General Manager.  

Is GUAC a big thing in your neck of the woods?  It always amazes me how restaurants can manage their avocado stock.  Our are usually either rock hard or over ripe with only a few hour window of perfection.

@John Carson 

The key to avocado management is to recognize when they are ripe and then get them into the refrigerator.  They can last about 15 minutes once cut open (which is why some restaurants make the GUAC table-side); about a day on the counter, and about a week in the fridge.

Color and softness are key to determining ripeness.  As soon as the skin starts to darken and the insides yield to the touch, get them into your electric icebox and they'll be good for a while.

@Steve L 
You are so right. I've been doing this and it really works.  The avocado is there and ready to go when you are ready to go at it.
Thanks for sharing.

@Vaer 

All good so far.  State of Emergency so most everything is shut down.  Folks still have to get to the Wawa though. 

It's quite cold, 24 degrees F, so the snow is very fine.  It's the border line freezing temps that are the concern as heavy snow/ice will bring down the power lines.

@John Carson 

Very nice one! Nice start to the week, getting the spangram first!! (Better than the world outside! Though it seems the sky finally is brightening here after what looks like a bit more than forecast -- a few inches of big wet flakes.) ❄️

The theme started making me hungry -- filling in the top first -- then I realized it was leaning towards fine dining. A celebration, even! Cheers! 🥂

@Xword Junkie 

and around here, SCAD is the Savannah College of Art and Design.

If they only had a football team, they'd be well known enough to use as a clue.

@Darren 
SCAD may be iffy, but it hardly ruins the whole puzzle.

There were plenty of fun entries, like BUSAN, ABHOR, and GOLDENDOODLE.

@Skeptical1 

Oopsie!  But in your defense, I can never keep that straight--just as I am never going to reliably know Right from Left.



Well, except in politics, where *I* believe Right is Wrong.

@Linda Jo 
Yes!  I looked up BUSAN--it's really pretty!  

Our dad was stationed in Uijongbu, South Korea.  One of his photos shows him standing beside a big sign reading "US ARMED FORCES:  THE LAW South of the 38th Parallel"  ....the year was 1957.

@Oikofuge 
I certainly remember the TV show (Oh, that Ilya Kuriakin! --Sp?  I much preferred David McCallum to Robert Vaughn)...but I guess I paid little to no attn to the credits.
I'm something of a punctuation terrorist (Eats, Shoots, and Leaves) ...though I don't carry a black marker with me any more.  Heh heh.

@Mean Old Lady 

Poor old Lynne Truss. Her "Eats, Shoots, And Leaves" got a savaging here in the New York Times, among other places.
A fine example of Muphry's Law in operation---if you make a point of criticizing someone else's spelling, punctuation or grammar, you'll inevitably violate your own "rules" while doing so.

@Oikofuge 
I know....but the title was such fun!
Then there is:  Let's eat Granny!  Punctuation saves lives!

@Scott 

Yes, my rule of "Never dine with dogs or children" meant that MENUS was a completely incomprehensible solution for me---the M at the cross with GMS went in purely for lack of anything better, given that I also didn't know what a "ball club" might be.
So, what? The children colour in the menus?
